A Spatial Analysis of Available Hospital Beds Relative to the Population Distribution in Texas Using Adaptive Bandwidth Log-Relative Risks

Michael Tiefelsdorf & Amanuel Abuhay

2020-08-14

1 Introduction

1.1 Motivation

News paper articles frequently discuss health care access in Texas, e.g., The Houston Public Media in June 2019, The Dallas Morning News in December 2019 and The Dallas Morning News in May 2020:

  • Texas has ranked last in access towards public health care and affordability.

  • The Texas Department of Health and Human services estimates a statewide shortage of 3,375 primary care physicians in Texas by 2030.

  • Some rural hospitals lack the financial resources to keep their doors open.

  • Around 3 million people live in rural Texas. They need to drive long distances to see their doctors and in case of an emergency they rely on helicopter ambulances.

1.2 Objectives

  • This study aims at identifying, depending on the location of hospitals, the ranges of their catchment areas.

  • Furthermore, areas of significant over- or under-supply of hospital capacities relative to the demand of their underlying population will be detected.

  • Potential causes for an unbalanced capacity distribution are evaluated.

1.3 Study Design

In contrast to other studies, a strict supply and demand approach is adopted in this study to evaluate spatial disparities in the provision of health care.

  1. Kernel density smoothers are used, because several counties lack having hospitals and to allow for cross-county spill-overs of the supply and demand.

  2. To account for a diverse distributions of the population and hospitals in a state as heterogeneous as Texas adaptive bandwidth kernel density smoothing needs to be employed.

    The detected adaptive bandwidths are estimating the spatial extent of the hospital’s catchment areas.

  3. The capacity weighted kernel densities of the hospital distribution is compared against the population weighted density of the block-group centroids.

    This relative risk ratio assesses for each location in Texas its hospital accessiblity.

  4. To account for commuting flows and spatial spill-overs of the population for health-care services across the Texas state line a 100 km guard buffer around Texas is introduced. This guard buffer provides more realistic estimates of the relative risk ratios for the border counties in Texas.

  5. Specific causes for a deviation of from a balanced distribution are evaluated using a heteroscedasticity adjusted linear regression model.

Geographic information system methodology and statistical methods available through several R-packages are employed in this study.

2 Relevant Map Layers

Most of this study’s data were obtained from Caliper Inc.. Caliper Inc. pre-processed and augmented the Center for Medicare & Medicaid Services Hospital Data as well as the most recent American Community Survey data of the U.S. Census Bureau.

Several map layers are needed for this state-wide hospital accessibility study in Texas:

  • A subset of the 655 Texas hospital locations with 74826 beds in total are used. The number of beds weights each hospital location and establishes the demand surface. The TYPE of an institution is used to filter irrelevant hospitals out.

  • Texas 15799 census block groups with their [a] population counts, [b] number of veterans and [c] army personal is needed to evaluate the demand for hospital beds.

    This fine spatial resolution allows modelling the extreme heterogeneous population distributions within the counties of West Texas and the Panhandle.

  • Texas 254 county polygons with their relevant attribute information is applied to identify potential determinants explaining any disparities in the hospital accessibility.

The spatial distribution of hospital locations in Texas clearly indicates that hospitals follow the population and cluster predominantly in urban and metropolitan areas.

## Check hospital locations
plot(countyShp, axes = TRUE, main = "Unweighted Hospital Locations in Texas")
points(hospitalShp, col = "red", pch = 20, cex = 0.5)

3.2 Definition of the Target Population

Since army personal and veterans frequent specialized hospitals and since their hospitals were not included in the analysis, the block group’s population needed to be adjusted. It is assumed that 50% of the veteran population utilize general hospitals.

## Update Population: civil = pop - army - veteran/2
bgShp$POPCIVIL <- bgShp$POPULATION - bgShp$INARMY - bgShp$VETERAN/2

3.3 Map Projection to UTM

The kernel density analysis requires isotrophy, i.e., equal distance units along the longitude and latitude. Therefore, the map layers needed to be re-projected into the UTM coordinates within zone 14 for Texas.

## project to UTM zone=14
projUTM <- CRS("+proj=utm +zone=14 +units=km")
hospitalUTM <- spTransform(hospitalShp, projUTM)
bgUTM <- spTransform(bgShp, projUTM)
txBufUTM <- spTransform(txBufShp, projUTM)
countyUTM <- spTransform(countyShp, projUTM)
TXStateLineUTM <- spTransform(TXStateLine, projUTM)

3.4 Conversion into a Raster Grid

The hospital locations and block group centroids were converted into point-pattern-objects, A raster mask with a grid cell resolution of 5 by 5 kilometers was setup and the county polygons were approximated by this raster mask.

## Define resolution of mask in kilometers
win <- as.mask(as.owin(txBufUTM), eps = 5)
unitname(win) <- list("km", "km")  #set the unit to kilometer  polygonal window

## Generate PPP objects for kernel density
pts <- coordinates(hospitalUTM)
hospitalPts <- ppp(pts[, 1], pts[, 2], window = win)
## Warning: data contain duplicated points
pts <- coordinates(bgUTM)
bgPts <- ppp(pts[, 1], pts[, 2], window = win)

4 Weighted Adaptive Kernel Density

For a given set of sample locations \(\left\{s_{1},s_{2}, \cdots, s_{n}\right\}\) and weights \(\left\{w_{1},w_{2}, \cdots, w_{n}\right\}\) the adaptive kernel densities bandwidths are calculated in a two step process:

  1. Using a global bandwidth \(\tau_0\) the density of the weighted point distribution at each pixel location \(s\) is explored by \[ \lambda_{\tau_0}(s) = \frac{1}{\sum_{i=1}^{n} w_i} \cdot \sum_{i=1}^{n} \frac{1}{\tau_0^2} \cdot w_i \cdot k\left( \frac{s-s_i}{\tau_0} \right) \]

    This intensity measure \(\lambda_{\tau_0}(s)\) provides a pilot estimate on which the local bandwidths \(\tau(s_i)\) will be based.

  2. Then adaptive bandwidth \(\tau(s_i)\) at each location \(s_i\) is calculated using the exploratory density \(\lambda_{\tau}(s)\) with \[ \tau(s_i) = \tau_0 \cdot \left( \frac{\lambda_g}{\lambda_{\tau_0}(s_i)} \right)^\alpha \] with \(\lambda_g = \sqrt[n]{\lambda_{\tau_0}(s_1) \cdot \lambda_{\tau_0}(s_2) \cdots \lambda_{\tau_0}(s_n) }\) being the geometric mean. The generalization parameter \(\alpha\) is usually set to \(\alpha=0.5\).

    The local bandwidth \(\tau(s_i)\) are varying around the global bandwidth \(\tau_0\). The local bandwidth shrinks in areas with a high pilot intensity and expands for areas with a low pilot intensity

An isotropic bi-variate normal distribution defines the kernel density function \(k(\cdot)\). The Diggle edge correction has been applied. Despite having a guard area around Texas’s state-line this edge correction is necessary to handle the truncated kernel densities along the Mexican border, because it is unlikely that patients seek hospitalization across an international border.

4.1 Hospital Surface

## bivariate density of hospital beds
hospitalKD <- bivariate.density(hospitalPts, h0 = 20, adapt = TRUE, weights = hospitalUTM$BEDS, 
    edge = "diggle", xy = bivarDensXY(win))
## ================================================================================
hosTitle <- expression(paste("Adaptive Bandwidth of Weighted Hospitals with ", tau[0] == 
    20, " km"))
plot(hospitalKD$him, main = hosTitle)
plot(stateLineTess, border = "green", add = TRUE)
box()
axis(1)
axis(2)

The adaptive bandwidth clearly varies around the fixed global bandwidth of \(\tau_0^{bed} = 20\) kilometers:

  • In areas with a dense placement of hospitals the adaptive bandwidth drops to \(\tau^{bed}(s_i)=10\) kilometers (~6 miles), which for urban areas is equivalent to approximately 20 minutes of travel time.
  • In contrast, for sparsely populated rural areas the adaptive bandwidth increase to up to \(\tau^{bed}(s_i)=100\) kilometers, which is equivalent to roughly 60 minutes of travel time.

4.2 Block Group Surface

## bivariate density block group populations
bgKD <- bivariate.density(bgPts, h0 = 15, adapt = TRUE, weights = bgShp$POPCIVIL, 
    edge = "diggle", xy = bivarDensXY(win))
## ================================================================================
bgTitle <- expression(paste("Adaptive Bandwidth of Weighted Block Groups with ", 
    tau[0] == 15, " km"))
plot(bgKD$him, main = bgTitle)
plot(stateLineTess, border = "green", add = TRUE)
box()
axis(1)
axis(2)

The selected global bandwidth \(\tau_0^{pop}=15\) kilometers was identified iteratively. It lead to a log-relative risk surface without major artifacts and a balanced distribution of the estimated log-relative risk values around the neutral value of zero.

It is reasonable to assume for the specialized services of hospitals to have larger market areas (i.e., \(\tau_0^{bed} = 20\)) than for the residents of areal units, whose daily activity field (i.e., \(\tau_0^{pop}=15\)) +usually is more constraint.

See the appendix for the alternative specifications of the population’s global bandwidths, that is, \(\tau_0^{pop}=10\) and \(\tau_0^{pop}=20\) kilometers.

5 Log-Relative Risk Surface with Significance Evaluation

The log-relative risk (LRR) compares the hospital bed supply density estimates \(f_{bed}(s)\) against the population density demand estimates \(f_{pop}(s)\) for each pixel location \(s\) by

\[ LLR(s) = \log \left(\frac{f_{bed}(s)}{f_{pop}(s)} \right) \] We observe for \[ LLR(s) =\left\{ \begin{array}{ll} < 0 & \mbox{under-supply} \\ \sim 0 & \mbox{balanced supply}\\ > 0 & \mbox{over-supply} \end{array} \right. \] of the hospital capacities relative the population demand.

## Risk surface
bivarateLRR <- risk(hospitalKD, bgKD, verbose = TRUE)

## Significance evaluation
tolLRR <- tolerance(bivarateLRR, method = "ASY", ITER = 100, verbose = TRUE, beta = 0.025)
## Initialising window...Done.
## Convolving bandwidth-categorised kernels with window:
##  --pass 1...Done.
##  --pass 2...Done.
##  --pass 3...Done.
##  --pass 4...Done.
## Plot logRR and significance
bound <- max(abs(range(bivarateLRR$rr$v, na.rm = TRUE)))

riskTitle <- expression(paste("LRR Surface with ", tau[0]^{
    bed
} == 20, " km & ", tau[0]^{
    pop
} == 15, " km and Significance Contours"))

plot(bivarateLRR, main = riskTitle, breaks = seq(-bound, bound, length.out = 16 + 
    1), col = diverge_hsv(16))
tol.contour(tolLRR, test = "lower", levels = c(0.05, 0.1, 0.5, 0.9, 0.95), col = "black", 
    add = TRUE)
plot(hospitalPts, col = "red", pch = 20, cex = 0.4, add = T)
plot(stateLineTess, border = "green", add = TRUE)
box()
axis(1)
axis(2)

This map displays two layers of information:

  • The pixel layer is the log-relative risk, with red pixels indicating an over-supply of hospital beds relative to the population distributions and blue pixels vice versa.

  • The isoline layer evaluates the significance, depicted here by the cumulative distribution function of the log-relative risk, of areas having excessive under-supply (\(p < 0.05\)) and over-supply (\(p > 0.95\)).

For Texas specific spatial pattern in the log-relative risk emerge:

  • While immediate metropolitan cores - such as Dallas-Fort Worth, Houston, San Antonio and Austin - usually experience an over-supply their immediate periphery is under-supplied, because of a higher population numbers in the periphery relative to the cores and a concentration of major hospitals in the cores.

    Hospitals in smaller urban areas - such as Corpus Christi, Victoria, Galveston, Waco, Tyler, Texarkana, Paris, Gainswille, Wichia Falls and Amarillo - service their hinterlands better.

  • Relative to the population density, the hospital supply for the mainly rural regions of the Edwards Plateau and the Low Rolling Plains in Central Texas and part of the Panhandle is higher than expected.

    Whereas, sparsely the populated Trans-Pecos in West Texas is under-supplied.

  • The supply status along the Mexican border is mixed. The urban centers - such as Brownsville, McAllen, Laredo and to a minor degree El Paso - experience over-supply, most of the smaller communities along the border are under-supplied.

6 Hospital Accessibility by County

The individual log-relative risk pixel estimates are aggregated into the county level. For each county the following aggregated measures are used:

  • The mean log-relative risk value LRRDens will become the target variable in a subsequent linear regression model.

  • The variance LRRVar of the log-relative risk pixel values within each county allows capturing the degrees of uncertainty of the mean log-relative risk estimate LRRDens by implementing a heteroscedasticity adjustment to the regression model.

## Aggregate kernel pixels into counties
riskStats <- densityKernelFct(bivarateLRR$rr, cntyTessIm)  # 
summary(riskStats)

7 Model Identification

7.1 Relevant Explanatory Variables

At the first step the influence of potential explanatory variables on the the spatial disparity of hospital accessibility is explored:

  • The political orientation (REPUBLIC)of a county may indicate a potential leverage to obtain funding for local hospitals as well as a general mindset of the counties population towards health care.
  • A high proportion of uninsured population (UNINSURED)stresses the health care supply.
  • Counties with an older population (MEDAGE)will demand more health care.
  • A high birth rate (BIR15TO50)in a county increases the demand for health care.
  • Distance from the Mexican border (DISTMEX)reflects a cultural shift in attitudes in the county’s residents.
  • The percentage of black population (PARTBLACK) may indicate disparities based on racial grounds.
  • The percentage of hispanic population (HISPORG)may point towards disparities based on cultural grounds.
  • The percentages of population with college degrees (COLLEGEDEG) or living in poverty (POVERTY) may hint at disparities based on socio-economic factors.

These proposed variables have the potential to explain any observed over- or under-supply for hospital beds in a county and enable political decision makers to take action.

The variables BIR15TO50, PARTBLACK and POVERTY have a few observations being equal to zero. These zeros prohibit determining their Box-Cox transformation parameters \(\lambda\) in order to explore whether their distributions would benefit from the symmetry transformation \(x^{[\lambda]}=\frac{(x^\lambda-1)}{\lambda}\). Thus, offset terms equal to their 5% quantile values were added these variable to achieve an all positive support.

7.3 Heteroscedasticity Regression Model

Due to the calculation of the dependent variable LRRDENS as average pixel value within the county boundaries, a variance is associated with LRRDENS. This causes heteroscedasticity in the regression model.

The weighted regression model lm.03 accounts for this heteroscedasticity through an estimated weights variable weights=lm.02$weights, which was determined in the lmHetero function of the model lm.02.

## heteroscedasticity investigation
lm.02 <- lmHetero(LRRDens ~ I(REPUBLIC^3) + DISTMEX + log(PARTBLACK + 0.01) + RELIGADHER | 
    log(LRRVar), data = countyShp)
summary(lm.02)

## build weighted OLS model

    weights = lm.02$weights, data = countyShp)
car::vif(lm.03)
##                           GVIF Df GVIF^(1/(2*Df))
## I(REPUBLIC^3)         1.705400  1        1.305910
## DISTMEX               2.020058  1        1.421287
## log(PARTBLACK + 0.01) 1.696286  1        1.302415
## RELIGADHER            1.111550  3        1.017782

From the proposed set of initial variables a group of relevant explanatory variables were identified in several rounds of exploring different model specifications.

Interpretation of the heteroscedastic model:

  • Overall, 24% of the variation in the dependent variable LRRDENS was explained by this weighted regression model.
  • The significant positive gamma coefficient of log(LRRVar) demonstrates that, as expected, the residual variance increases with the variance of the counties’s log-relative risk estimate.
  • Counties leaning Republican have better access to hospital beds. This may be due to stronger leverage of republican led counties to obtain health care funding or a greater value placed on health care.
  • Counter-intuitively, counties further away from the Mexican border have less access to hospital beds.
  • Interestingly, the Afro-american population is better served by hospital beds, either due to a higher demand or political leverage.
  • With growing religious adhesion within a county the provision of hospital beds is increasing. This may indicate a strong sense of community sentiments.
  • As the variance inflation factors VIFs indicate, the weighted regression model is not affected by multicollinearity.
## Effects plots
plot(allEffects(lm.03), ylim = c(-0.9, 0.3), main = "Variable Effects on Hospital Accessibility")

The model diagnostics for the weighted regression model show a lack of major violations of the model’s assumptions.

7.4.2 Outliers

## residual scan
car::influenceIndexPlot(lm.03, id = list(n = 3, labels = countyShp$NAME), main = "Residual Diagnostics")

The only outlier according to Bonferroni \(p\)-values of the studentized residuals is Howard County along interstate 20 in the southern part of the High Plains. Its over-supply is substantially higher than expected based on the explanatory variables.

The residuals are normally distributed. None of the studentized residual is outside the confidence envelop.

The weighted residual pattern exhibits substantial spatial clustering in the regression residuals and strong positive spatial autocorrelation.

8.2 Correlogram

## Correlogram
plot(sp.correlogram(link, wResid, order=12,          # correlogram
                    method="I", style = "W"), 
     main="Correlogram of Supply- and Demand Model")

The slowly vanishing and, perhaps, oscillating autocorrelation level for increasing spatial lags in correlogram indicates that the underlying data generating mechanism is more complex than what would be expected either for

  • a simultaneous autoregressive (SAR) process or
  • a spatial lag (LAG) process.

Consequently, neither the SAR nor the LAG models will provide meaningful estimates for this potentially non-stationary data generating process.

9 Conclusions

This study as shown, while the travel distances in rural Texas are substantially longer to obtain access to health care, that the provision of health care relative to the population density is adequate for most areas.

9.1 Key Findings

  • Adaptive bandwidth kernel estimation is preferred over fixed bandwidth for regions that are as heterogeneous as Texas:

    • for urbanized areas the average travel distance was around 10 km (~20 minutes travel time), whereas
    • for remote rural areas the distance increased to 100 km (~60 minutes travel time).

  • Counties, which surround metropolitan cores, are generally under-served.

  • Interestingly, sparsely populated rural counties in central Texas and the Panhandle as well as some counties along the Mexican border experienced an over-supply relative to their population demanding health care.

  • The Republican political affiliation of a county’s population as well as religious adhesion favorably led to an over-supply of hospital capacities. So did a strong Afro-american population segment, which mainly is concentrated in metropolitan cores.

9.2 Model Refinements

  • Rather than using adaptive weighted kernel densities based on euclidean distances, densities based on travel times along the state’s street network can be evaluated.

  • Rather than aggregating the log-relative risk kernel pixels into counties, the analysis could be repeated on the census tract level. This finer spatial resolution may reveal, subject to available data, further relevant factors capturing any over- or under-supply patterns.

    Having this analysis encoded as a R Markdown document easily enables reproduction of this study with an augmented dataset.

    However, one needs to bear in mind that decisions such as opening or closing a hospital, its location and capacity regularly require the involvement of broader jurisdictions on the county level.

9.3 Possible Generalizations

  • Log-relative risk ratios are frequently used in epidemiological studies to compare the density of cases with a particular diseases and ailments against the density of controls comprising of the underlying population at risk.

  • Log-relative risk ratios are less frequently used in economic settings to evaluate imbalances between the local demand and supply for goods and services as well as the identification of of the range of market areas. Log-relative risk ratios clearly provide a methodology for further economic studies.

  • By integrating log-relative risk ratio pixels into larger statistical units, aggregated discrepancies can be linked to external areal characteristics. This additional information allows explaining observed discrepancies in a regression setting.
